    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-02-17T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-02-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">684A.85/2–1750: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Israel</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McDonald</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-02-17T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 17, 1950—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. At my request Shiloah with Kollek<note n="1" xml:id="d360fn1">Theodore
                        (Teddy) Kollek, Director of the North American Division of the Israeli
                        Ministry for Foreign Affairs.</note> at residence, February 16 said he and
                    possibly Dayan to meet with Abdullah and Samir (Geneva <pb facs="0770" n="748"
                        xml:id="pg_748"/> for <gloss target="#t_USPCC1">USPCC</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_USTC1">USTC</gloss>) night February 17 in Transjordan. Shiloah’s
                    letter of “few days ago” to Samir recalling their agreement February 3 on
                    another meeting was not answered; but Shiloah’s later indirect approach to Samir
                    was promptly accepted.</p>
                <p>Shiloah said he is not optimistic. Confident King still wants agreement but fears
                    he may not be able build Cabinet willing to take responsibility for agreement
                    with Israel. Shiloah credits Samir with intelligent, earnest desire secure
                    settlement and being willing risk much to get it.</p>
                <p>Information Shiloah gave me re Transjordan Cabinet meeting February 13 was
                    similar that Amman <gloss target="#t_Legtel1">Legtel</gloss> 10 February
                        13.<note n="2" xml:id="d360fn2">This telegram was a repeat of No. 22 from
                        Amman, <ref target="#pg_741">p. 741</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Comment:</hi> I believe Shiloah as usual is telling truth but
                    not necessarily whole truth. <hi rend="italic">End comment</hi>.</p>
                <p>[Here follows the last paragraph, dealing with the health of Prime Minister
                    Ben-Gurion.]</p>
                <p>Sent Department 119, repeated Jerusalem 10, Department pass Geneva 1, London
                    29.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McDonald</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
